So, The Old Admiralty Office was the headquarters of the British Navy.

00:05:10.534 --> 00:05:16.704
And this word, combined with the date that this was built, 1726, gives

00:05:16.744 --> 00:05:22.114
us some indication about why this new “office” might have been required.

00:05:23.204 --> 00:05:28.524
It was just as the British Empire was starting, as British ships sailed around the

00:05:28.544 --> 00:05:34.364
world looking for new territories, new people to colonise, new dominions to rule over.

00:05:35.544 --> 00:05:40.774
We’ll skip over any discussion of the morality of this, but what is

00:05:40.774 --> 00:05:46.764
undeniable is that it was a very large, gargantuan, sprawling, organisation.

00:05:47.504 --> 00:05:51.974
Lots of people were involved, information needed to be shared,

00:05:52.244 --> 00:05:56.244
documents written, decisions to be made, orders to be given.

00:05:57.424 --> 00:06:01.824
There needed to be a centralised physical location where all of this

00:06:02.294 --> 00:06:07.744
would take place, and this was The Old Admiralty Office in central London.

00:06:09.254 --> 00:06:14.214
Strangely enough, the office is still standing, it’s used by the British government

00:06:14.474 --> 00:06:20.244
as the headquarters of the Department of International Trade, so funnily enough not

00:06:20.374 --> 00:06:25.804
all that much has changed in the almost 300 years since the building was first used.

